{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BdcE2mr4ja5vYA7h1VrEeD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This involves the AI vision model classifying an image AND the downstream logic holding it. The failure could be in the AI model itself OR in the pipeline logic. The core question: is the failure at a module boundary or does it depend on real AI?\n- REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network/subprocess needed inherently.\n- MOCK-HIDE: If we mock the AI model to return \"explicit\", we can test the pipeline logic. But the actual classification of explicit content depends on a real LLM/vision model.\n\n\n- LLM-DEP: The behavior fundamentally requires a real AI vision model to correctly identify explicit content in images—I can't verify this works without actually running the model against explicit material.\n- MULTI-STEP: No multiple agentic steps.\n\nMinimum level: **Agentic** - the behavior depends on verifying that a real AI vision model correctly classifies explicit content.\n\n**Behavior 2: A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This centers on the AI text model's ability to detect hate speech even when it's disguised through various obfuscation methods.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes—the core question is whether the real AI model can handle obfuscation, not just detect straightforward hate speech. Mocking the model to return \"hate speech\" doesn't actually test this capability.\n\nMinimum level: **Agentic**\n\n**Behavior 3: A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about the pipeline's routing logic—when both checks pass, does the system actually publish the post?\n- REAL-INFRA: No real infrastructure needed.\n- LLM-DEP: I can mock both AI models to return \"safe\" and test whether the downstream publish logic works correctly. The behavior is really about what happens when both checks pass.\n\nMinimum level: **Integration**—I need the image check module, text check module, and publish decision all wired together. The failure would likely occur at the module boundaries, though if there's a single decision function that handles \"if both_pass: publish()\", it could be Unit-level.\n\n**Behavior 4: The full moderation pipeline completes within 5 seconds of submission.**\n\n- REAL-INFRA: This is a performance test that requires real infrastructure to measure throughput under load.\n- LLM-DEP: The completion time depends on actual AI model latency. Mocking would always pass, but real calls might exceed the 5-second SLA.\n- MULTI-STEP: The pipeline chains multiple real AI calls—vision model for images, text model for content, then the publish decision—so this is a Workflow-level test.\n\nMinimum level: **Workflow**\n\n**Behavior 5: When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.**\n\nThis is testing error handling behavior—specifically whether the system queues for retry or auto-approves when the vision service fails. I can mock the unavailability by having the vision service throw an exception, so I don't need a real AI model. The key is whether the error handler correctly routes to the queue versus auto-approval. This involves multiple modules wired together (vision service, error handler, queue), making it an Integration-level test. The question is whether I need a real queue or if a mock suffices.\n\nFor the consistency behavior, I'm looking at whether a borderline image gets the same moderation decision across multiple submissions. This requires a real AI model since the behavior specifically tests for consistency in actual model outputs—a mock would always return the same thing and wouldn't capture the real non-determinism of the AI. The test involves submitting the same image multiple times and verifying consistent decisions.\n\nThough there's a possibility the system uses caching to ensure consistency, the behavior description doesn't mention that—it's asking about the moderation decision itself being consistent, which is fundamentally an AI model property. So this falls into Agentic territory.\n\nNow I'm moving on to assign the probability levels for each behavior.\n\nFor the explicit image flagging, the core question is whether I can test this with a mocked AI or if I need the real model to verify it actually detects explicit content—that pushes it to Agentic minimum, with probabilities heavily weighted there at 0.75.\n\nHate speech with obfuscation definitely requires real AI since the model needs to understand the disguised language, so that's also Agentic-heavy at 0.80.\n\nFor the clean post being published, I'm looking at whether this is about pipeline routing logic or if the AI's judgment is what matters.\n\nThe 5-second SLA is a full end-to-end performance test with real AI calls across multiple steps, which makes it a Workflow-level concern at 0.60 probability.\n\nWhen the vision model becomes unavailable and triggers a queue retry, that's error handling I can mostly mock, so Integration level at 0.65 is appropriate.\n\nFor borderline images where consistency matters, I need the real AI to evaluate what counts as borderline.\n\nNow I'm looking at Behavior 6 with the non-determinism aspect—that's inherently an Agentic-level test at 0.70 probability since the AI's variability is what I'm testing.\n\nLet me refine the minimum levels and double-check that the plan_consistent self-check actually works. For Behavior 3, if I have a single function that decides an action based on both image and text results, that could technically be Unit-level, but since it requires the full pipeline flow with both content checks and publishing, Integration is the right call. Behavior 4 stays Workflow because it chains multiple agentic steps—image check, text check, and timing measurement. For Behavior 5, the error handling could be Unit if I'm just testing the retry logic in isolation, but the vision model unavailability needs to be realistic enough that Integration makes more sense.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9910,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9910},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"20c82ae6-3472-4743-b64e-116cad94896a","uuid":"a679c199-2a0e-46eb-a991-46dccd189849"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BdcE2mr4ja5vYA7h1VrEeD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01YXLLrJqor6bUmiNKv6zhQr","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"An image containing explicit content is flagged and held for review, not published.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The pipeline routing logic (flag → hold) could be tested with a mocked model, but that is not what this behavior asserts. It asserts that the real AI vision model correctly classifies an explicit image. LLM-DEP: Correctness depends on what the real AI vision model produces for a given explicit image. Mocking the model to return 'explicit' trivially passes without verifying the model actually fires on real explicit content. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: a mocked vision model always returns the pre-programmed label — the failure mode (explicit content not caught by the model) would never surface.","test_description":"Submit a real image containing explicit content to the moderation pipeline using the live AI vision model. Assert that the pipeline result is 'held for review' and the post is not published.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A text post containing hate speech is flagged regardless of obfuscation techniques (e.g., letter substitution, unicode lookalikes).","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The entire claim rests on whether the real AI text model handles obfuscation robustly. Mocking the model to return 'hate speech' for an obfuscated string proves nothing about the model's actual behavior — it hides the exact failure mode the behavior is designed to catch. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: a mocked text classifier will pass any input we configure it to pass; real robustness to unicode lookalikes and letter substitution can only be verified against the live model.","test_description":"Submit text posts with hate speech expressed via letter substitution and unicode lookalikes to the live AI text classification model. Assert each variant is flagged regardless of obfuscation technique.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.09}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A post that passes both content checks is published rather than held or silently dropped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in the routing logic after both models return safe — a wiring bug between modules (e.g., a double-negative, a default-deny fallback, or a silent drop on an unhandled code path). Both AI models can be stubbed to return 'safe'; no real AI output is needed. LLM-DEP: None — we are testing the control flow conditional on safe results, not the classifier quality. MOCK-HIDE: Using real AI could cause flaky results on borderline inputs; a stub cleanly isolates the routing logic. REJECTION-GATE for Unit: 'published rather than held or silently dropped' implies the image check module, text check module, and publish gate must all be wired together — a single function unit test cannot catch a dropped handoff between them.","test_description":"Wire image-check, text-check, and publish modules together with both classifiers stubbed to return 'safe'. Submit a neutral post and assert the pipeline outcome is 'published', not 'held' or silently absent.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full moderation pipeline — image check, text check, publish decision — completes within 5 seconds of submission.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: 'Full moderation pipeline' is explicitly the sequence: submission → real AI vision call → real AI text call → publish decision. That is two independent real LLM/vision model calls chained in sequence, satisfying the Workflow criterion. LLM-DEP: Real model latency drives whether the 5-second SLA is met; in-process stubs return instantly and always pass. REAL-INFRA: End-to-end wall-clock timing depends on real network round-trips to both AI services. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic (single step): the behavior requires both the image model and the text model to complete in sequence — a single-model Agentic test would not catch the cumulative latency budget.","test_description":"Submit a post with both an image and text through the live full pipeline (real AI vision model, real AI text model, publish decision) and measure wall-clock time from submission to final decision. Assert completion under 5 seconds.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.23,"Workflow":0.65}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the AI vision model is unavailable, image posts are queued for retry rather than auto-approved.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is in the error-handling branch when the vision service throws an unavailability error — the system must route to the retry queue rather than default-approving. The vision model's unavailability can be simulated by having the stub raise a connection/timeout error. LLM-DEP: None — we are not testing what the model classifies; we are testing the system's fallback behavior when the model cannot be reached. REAL-INFRA: An in-process stub that raises an exception reproduces the exact failure boundary (queue vs. auto-approve); a real unavailable endpoint is not needed. REJECTION-GATE for Unit: 'queued for retry' requires the error-handling code, the queue component, and the vision service client to be wired together — a single function unit test cannot catch a missing enqueue call.","test_description":"Configure the vision service client stub to raise an unavailability exception. Submit an image post and assert the post appears in the retry queue and is not marked as approved or published.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The moderation decision for a borderline image is consistent when the same image is submitted multiple times within a short window.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: A 'borderline' image is by definition one where the real AI model's output is near its classification threshold. Consistency under repeated submission is an empirical claim about real model behavior (temperature, sampling stochasticity). With a mock, the return value is deterministic by construction — the mock always passes trivially and the behavior's actual failure mode (real model flip-flopping on borderline content) is invisible. MOCK-HIDE: Any stub returns the same label every time, making the test vacuous. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: even with caching logic wired in, the test cannot verify that cache-miss paths produce consistent AI outputs without calling the real model.","test_description":"Submit the same borderline image (near classification threshold) to the live AI vision pipeline at least 5 times within a short window. Assert all decisions are identical, verifying the system (whether via caching or model determinism) delivers a consistent outcome.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.72,"Workflow":0.08}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9910,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9910},"output_toke